        body: ["Painful intercourse is a complaint that is difficult to talk about; many patients accept it as normal for a long time. Yet the first question should not be can you manage it but where is the pain, when does it start, and what does it accompany.", "Dryness, vaginal atrophy, infections, scar tissue, persistent pelvic floor muscle tension, postpartum changes and relationship anxiety can all create the same presentation. Treatment is also not a single option; moisturisers, lubricants, local treatments, dilators, pelvic floor support or other medical approaches are considered individually.", "Pain should not be accepted as a natural part of sexuality. When the map of the problem is drawn, both the body's response and the patient's relational confidence can be supported more accurately."],
